childNodes.text: Apple doesn't care about their customers!!!

This review will be as much about about Apple as a company and the way they treat their customers, as it is about the actual product which DID failed 2 months out of warranty at no fault of the owner.
My son got his MacBook Pro when he started college last year. Instead of buying him a $400 laptop, we splurged on a Macbook Pro for more than 3 times the price. It was a splurge, but we figured spread out over 4 years it's okay. Well, the computer only lasted 1 year and 2 months. Then the screen turned in 6 vertical pink bars when opened more than 90 degrees. See picture) After several stops at the Apple Store and multiple calls to tech support in California, these are my findings:
1) Apple acknowledged that my son was very unlucky and ended up with a (according to Apple very rare) defective product, not his fault. If this would have been a car, the LEMON LAW would have applied.
2) EVERYONE at Apple told us we should have bought the extended warranty (I guess paying a premium price for a premium product doesn't mean anything anymore...). Your APPLE product MOST LIKELY will fail before it is 3 years old. Reassuring words directly from the selling company (sarcasm).
3) We were 2 months out of warranty, the Macbook looked like new. No dents, scratches or anything. TOO BAD, out of warranty is out of warranty. Upfront cost to fix the problem $475 (!!!!)
4) The Apple tech guys in California told me to go back to the Apple Store (at Coconut Point in Estero, FL) and plead with a manager for a fair solution because everyone agreed that it was NOT our doing that the Macbook Pro broke. It clearly was a hardware failure INSIDE the Macbook Pro.
5) Going back to the Apple Store and talking to the manager got me nowhere. The manager told me literally that Apple's responsibility to it's shareholders is MORE IMPORTANT to them than helping out it's customers. When I asked him that this means that I am out of luck (I actually used a different phrase but I cannot put that in this review), he simply said YES you are.

So now I have an unusable Macbook Pro in "like new" condition with the option of spending almost $500 on a USED and out of warranty product or just throwing it out and buy something else. I hate throwing good money after bad, so I will have to buy my son another computer. This time it will not be an Apple. As a matter of fact, I will never buy an Apple product again for as long as I live. I will phase out the 6 iPhones I have in my family and I will encourage everyone to learn from my experience. It can happen to you too!! Apple does NOT care about you.

On a final note; under the agreement that Best Buy has with Apple, Best Buy is NOT ALLOWED to touch Apple computers for repair, even if the Apple product is out of warranty. Also, Apple purposely designs it's products in such a way that it is virtually impossible to fix any problems. As you know, you cannot add memory to your MacBook or iPhone, you cannot add your hard drive capacity, you cannot replace your battery, the screen is glued in and cannot be replaced without replacing the entire top shell of the Macbook, on and on and on. So Apple has put everything in place VERY DELIBERATELY to make sure that you cannot fix your product when you encounter a problem. A despicable company. WOULD NOT RECOMMEND.
Apple - MacBook Pro - 13" Display - Intel Core i5 - 8 GB Memory - 256GB Flash Storage - Space Gray

childNodes.text:
The 13" MacBook Pro (latest 2017 model) is a great laptop. I have always loved Apple products for its performance, design etc.,I already own iPhone, iPad and this is the first Macbook. It is great to have them all sync and bunch of other features working together. MacBook Pro 13.3 is a good size, , you can see and read everything on the screen really well, with Retina display pictures are more vibrant and brighter. The laptop is fast with the SSD booting macOS. The new keyboard layout is great as well. Many complain about the noise when typing. I don't use keyboard much so I don't have any complaints. However, if you're used to Apple keyboards you'll love it. They last, they look good, they work.
If this your first Macbook purchase, I would say Buy it!!, you won't be disappointed.

childNodes.text: After installing the newest Mac OS how much room is left on the 256gb ssd?

A bit over 230gb. Mac OS Sierra is about 17~18gb on the MacBook Pro I purchased 2 weeks ago (promptly updated). Of course, that does not include the apps already on the system. With pre-installed apps, you're looking at something like 220gb (+/- 5gb). There are quite a few gigs which can be freed up there.
